    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-01-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-01-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="416" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d416">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 416.</seg>
                </opener>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Morgan</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-01-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 1, 1885</date>.
                            (Received January 9.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 960.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Yesterday Mr. Thomas R. Monahan called at the
                        legation. He informed me that a few days ago the judge of the federal court
                        at Toluca sent for him and informed him that he had been “honorably
                        acquitted,” and was therefore discharged. He also stated that the judge had
                        exacted a promise from him to appear in case the supreme court should
                        reverse the judgment. He was not tried but simply discharged, he says.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>P. H. MORGAN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
